Plan Item #179697: Add `FragmentShader.getUniformVecX`

## description

Today we have `FragmentShader.getUniformFloat(String name, {int index = 0})`.  This is cumbersome for setting things like vec4s.  https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/177185 proposes an improvement to setting individual floats.  This is a proposal that allows us to set vectors in one argument.

## proposal

We add: 
- `UniformVec4Slot`, `UniformVec3Slot`, and `UniformVec2Slot`, which mirror `UniformFloatSlot`
- `UniformVec4Slot FragmentShader.getUniformVec4(String name)` which mirrors `FragmentShader.getUniformFloat`.  Same for the other vector types.
- `UniformVec4Slot.set(double, double, double, double)` which mirror `UniformFloatSlot.set`.  Same for other vector types.
-  `UniformVectorSlot` which is a slot that can be of any arbitrary size, this allows for setting arrays and matrices easier.

These new types will be built off of `UniformFloatSlot` so we get the work we did with hot reloading.

## example

```dart
void setColor(FragmentShader shader) {
  UniformVec4Slot color = shader.getUniformVec4('u_color');
  color.set(0.0, 1.0, 0.0, 0.0);
}

void setArray(FragmentShader shader) {
  UniformVectorSlot array = shader.getUniformVector(5, 'u_array');
  array.set([0.0, 1.0, 0.0, 0.0, 2.0]);
}
```

## alternatives considered

### Just add `UniformVectorSlot`

Adding the different types for each vector size allows us to have compile time validation on supplying the correct number of arguments.  This has the benefit of also supporting arrays and matrices easily.

### Expand `UniformFloatSlot` to accomodate vectors

We could just add one new method to UniformFloatSlot, `setVector(List<double>)` or ones like `setVec4(double, double, double, double)`.  This would require us to throw arity errors when setting slots happens, not when slots are instantiated.  It's better to throw the error earlier and once when the slot is instantiated.

### Add named parameters setters

`void UniformVec4Slot.setColor({required double r, required double g, required double b, required double a});`

These provide the convenience of having named parameters but they are more typing.  I don't think anyone would probably use them.  Unless `set` used the `xyzw` names and we just added `setColor`.  Then users would be forced to use named parameters one way or the other.

### Add optional named parameter setters

`void UniformVec4Slot.set({double? r, double? g, double? b, double? a, double? x, double? y, double? z, double? w});`

This forces people to use named parameters but there is some runtime checking that would be required to make sure people specify things correctly.  It also allows non-idiomatic orders of components which are pretty well established.

### Use records to support named parameters

```dart
void set(Object value) {
  switch (value) {
    case (double x, double y, double z, double w):
      break;
    case (:double r, :double g, :double b, :double a):
      break;
    case (:double x, :double y, :double z, :double w):
      break;
    default:
      throw Error();
  }
}
```

This is convenient to read, but not convenient to write because there is no mechanism in dart to for a compile-time validation that you've sent in the correct type.  It also induces extra memory allocations.

### Add datatypes for uniform data

`void UniformVec4Slot.set(Vec4 value)`

The use-case we are accommodating for in dart:ui is setting uniforms.  For that the custom datatypes are unnecessary.  Setting the slots directly requires less overhead since there isn't an intermediate object that is being allocated.  Also, in order for the new datatypes to not collide with existing projects and to have meaningful names in dart:ui they'd have to be named something like `UniformVec4` which becomes much more verbose than just using parameter arguments directly.

