}
```

This is convenient to read, but not convenient to write because there is no mechanism in dart to for a compile-time validation that you've sent in the correct type.  It also induces extra memory allocations.

### Add datatypes for uniform data

`void UniformVec4Slot.set(Vec4 value)`

The use-case we are accommodating for in dart:ui is setting uniforms.  For that the custom datatypes are unnecessary.  Setting the slots directly requires less overhead since there isn't an intermediate object that is being allocated.  Also, in order for the new datatypes to not collide with existing projects and to have meaningful names in dart:ui they'd have to be named something like `UniformVec4` which becomes much more verbose than just using parameter arguments directly.

